# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1894-washington-senators-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1894-washington-senators-season/1891-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1891 throughout the world.
[src:1894-washington-senators-season/1891-washington-statesmen-season] The **1891 Washington Statesmen** baseball team finished the season with a 44–91 record in the American Association in their first season.
[src:1894-washington-senators-season/1891-washington-statesmen-season] After the season, the AA disbanded and the Washington club, renamed the "Senators," joined the National League.
[src:1894-washington-senators-season/1892-washington-senators-season] The **1892 Washington Senators season** was a season in American professional baseball.
[src:1894-washington-senators-season/1892-washington-senators-season] The team, which had played in the now-defunct American Association in 1891 as the **Washington Statesmen**, was purchased by J.
[src:1894-washington-senators-season/1892-washington-senators-season] Earl Wagner and moved to the National League for the 1892 season.
[src:1894-washington-senators-season/1892-washington-senators-season] In a split season schedule, the Senators finished seventh in the first half of the season and last in the second half.
[src:1894-washington-senators-season/1892-washington-senators-season] Overall, the team had a record of 58–93, 10th-best in the 12-team National League.
[src:1894-washington-senators-season/1892-washington-senators-season] The Senators held spring training in Savannah, Georgia at Bolton Street Park.
[src:1894-washington-senators-season/1893-washington-senators-season] The **1893 Washington Senators** baseball team finished the season with a 40–89 record, last place in the National League.
[src:1894-washington-senators-season/1894-baltimore-orioles-season] The **Baltimore Orioles** won their first National League pennant in 1894.
[src:1894-washington-senators-season/1894-baltimore-orioles-season] After the regular season's conclusion, the Orioles participated in the first Temple Cup competition against the second-place New York Giants.
[src:1894-washington-senators-season/1894-baltimore-orioles-season] The Orioles lost to the Giants in a sweep, four games to none.
[src:1894-washington-senators-season/1894-baltimore-orioles-season] The Orioles roster contained six future Hall of Famers: Wilbert Robinson, John McGraw, Dan Brouthers, Hughie Jennings, Wee Willie Keeler and Joe Kelley.
[src:1894-washington-senators-season/1894-baltimore-orioles-season] Every man in their starting line-up hit .300 for the season.
[src:1894-washington-senators-season/1894-baltimore-orioles-season] They bunted, hit-and-ran, Baltimore chopped, backed up throws, cut off throws, and had pitchers cover first.
[src:1894-washington-senators-season/1894-baltimore-orioles-season] They also deadened balls by icing them, tilted baselines so bunts would roll fair, and put soap around the mound so an opposing pitcher would get slippery fingers if he tried to dry his hands in the dirt.
[src:1894-washington-senators-season/1894-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1894 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 24th season of the franchise.
[src:1894-washington-senators-season/1894-boston-beaneaters-season] The team finished in third place in the National League with a record 83–49–1 (.629), 8.0 games behind the Baltimore Orioles and 5.0 games behind the New York Giants.
[src:1894-washington-senators-season/1894-boston-beaneaters-season] As of 2025, the 1894 Beaneaters hold the MLB record for the most runs scored in a single season by one team with 1,220, a stunning 9.17 runs per contest; however, they also allowed 1,002 runs (7.53 runs allowed per game), the 33rd-most in baseball history.
[src:1894-washington-senators-season/1894-boston-beaneaters-season] The Beaneaters' home park, the South End Grounds, was destroyed in a fire on May 15.
[src:1894-washington-senators-season/1894-boston-beaneaters-season] The team played their home games at Congress Street Grounds until the rebuilt park opened on July 20.
[src:1894-washington-senators-season/1894-brooklyn-grooms-season] The **1894 Brooklyn Grooms** finished in fifth place in a crowded National League pennant race.
[src:1894-washington-senators-season/1894-washington-senators-season] The **1894 Washington Senators** baseball team finished the season with a 45–87 record, eleventh place in the National League.
